00:23:02,671 --> 00:23:06,133
When this happens, your brain actually extrapolates that pattern.

495
00:23:06,133 --> 00:23:09,634
If you ask me for money at 5 minutes and 10 minutes, I'm going to assume it's going to

496
00:23:09,634 --> 00:23:14,016
do it at 15, 20, 25, 30, so on and so forth, and I'm going to realize that your game is

497
00:23:14,016 --> 00:23:14,937
not free at all.

498
00:23:15,870 --> 00:23:21,273
By contrast, one of the design battles I won when we converted Star Wars The Old Republic

499
00:23:21,273 --> 00:23:27,575
to free-to-play was to not have any paywalls or pretty much any spend opportunities at

500
00:23:27,575 --> 00:23:29,516
all on the first planet of the game.

501
00:23:29,516 --> 00:23:31,397
That's three to four hours of gameplay.

502
00:23:31,397 --> 00:23:32,978
I had a really good reason for that.

503
00:23:32,978 --> 00:23:38,720
When we were a premium game, we tested the bejesus out of that first planet to the degree

504
00:23:38,720 --> 00:23:40,481
that the people running the test said that

505
00:23:40,761 --> 00:23:48,783
our first planet was the single best testing MMO starting experience they had ever seen.

506
00:23:48,783 --> 00:23:49,904
Why fuck that up?

507
00:23:49,904 --> 00:23:51,204
Right?

508
00:23:51,204 --> 00:23:53,945
Instead, let them fall in love with the game.

509
00:23:53,945 --> 00:23:56,545
Give them a whole planet so that they want to spin,

510
00:23:56,545 --> 00:23:58,526
so that they want to help your developers out,

511
00:23:58,526 --> 00:24:00,707
so that they want to take the developer's side.

512
00:24:04,238 --> 00:24:07,945
Remember how I said free-to-play players are good cannon fodder for big spinners?

513
00:24:07,945 --> 00:24:10,169
You have to be real careful with that.

514
00:24:10,169 --> 00:24:12,233
I mean it's not fun to get stomped.

515
00:24:12,233 --> 00:24:16,040
Now I'm not saying that free players should always be paired with other free players.

516
00:24:17,917 --> 00:24:21,878
But it's really important that if you have a PvP experience

517
00:24:21,878 --> 00:24:24,959
that you're giving them people that are just out of reach.

518
00:24:24,959 --> 00:24:26,699
That you're giving them something where maybe

519
00:24:26,699 --> 00:24:28,460
if they spent a little or if they invested

520
00:24:28,460 --> 00:24:30,641
a little more time or got a little more free gems

521
00:24:30,641 --> 00:24:32,801
that they would be able to beat that stuff.

522
00:24:32,801 --> 00:24:35,302
You don't want people to run into a wall

523
00:24:35,302 --> 00:24:38,443
and say that the only way it could possibly compete

524
00:24:38,443 --> 00:24:38,883
is to drop $1,000.

525
00:24:38,883 --> 00:24:41,904
Or you will drive them out of those game systems

526
00:24:41,904 --> 00:24:44,005
if you don't drive them out of the game altogether.

527
00:24:45,659 --> 00:24:49,562
In Dungeon Boss, the characters in our gem portal

528
00:24:49,562 --> 00:24:52,104
are much more powerful than the free players.

529
00:24:52,104 --> 00:24:55,806
And people who have spent them at a much easier time

530
00:24:55,806 --> 00:24:56,907
actually winning in PvP.

531
00:24:56,907 --> 00:24:58,568
This was a harsh lesson for us,

532
00:24:58,568 --> 00:25:00,109
that we really had to spend a lot of time

533
00:25:00,109 --> 00:25:03,291
massaging our matchmaking in order to bring that in line.

534
00:25:03,291 --> 00:25:06,053
Yeah, David beat Goliath, but this is a great story,

535
00:25:06,053 --> 00:25:12,457
largely because of how improbable it actually was.

536
00:25:12,457 --> 00:25:13,858
Most of the time,

537
00:25:14,462 --> 00:25:18,284
Goliath stomps David and David throws his iPad across the room.

538
00:25:18,284 --> 00:25:18,985
And then the last point is this.

539
00:25:18,985 --> 00:25:25,109
If you take all this together and you say, yeah, we really do need to get our free players

540
00:25:25,109 --> 00:25:31,953
to spend, be sure that they have a fun time, be sure that it's not too obnoxious, and then

541
00:25:31,953 --> 00:25:37,097
try to hint at them that spending just a little is going to have a big impact.

542
00:25:40,570 --> 00:25:43,935
Don't try to make them whales from day one.

543
00:25:43,935 --> 00:25:45,777
Try to get them to spend one dollar.

544
00:25:46,702 --> 00:25:49,623
make that first dollar really really an amazing value for them.

545
00:25:49,623 --> 00:25:53,044
Give them glimpses of what spending that first dollar is going to be like

546
00:25:53,044 --> 00:25:57,065
and then once you do, try to stair-step them up gradually.

547
00:25:57,065 --> 00:26:01,045
Now it's always going to be the case inside of free-to-play that the heavy

548
00:26:01,045 --> 00:26:04,006
spenders are going to do the heavy lifting in terms of supporting the

549
00:26:04,006 --> 00:26:07,107
gameplay. That is either a fortunate or unfortunate

550
00:26:07,107 --> 00:26:10,848
way of life for the free-to-play market right now, depending on your point of view.

551
00:26:11,768 --> 00:26:14,832
But at the same time, we have to keep in mind that most people

552
00:26:14,832 --> 00:26:15,393
aren't that.

553
00:26:15,393 --> 00:26:18,376
Most of our player base are free players,

554
00:26:18,376 --> 00:26:20,679
and they still add enormous value to the game.

555
00:26:20,679 --> 00:26:21,420
That's fine, and get used to it.

556
00:26:21,420 --> 00:26:22,401
In conclusion, free players are the normal ones.

557
00:26:22,401 --> 00:26:22,882
Design your game as such.

558
00:26:22,882 --> 00:26:23,503
Thank you very much.

559
00:26:38,797 --> 00:26:39,798
Thank you, Damien.

560
00:26:39,798 --> 00:26:42,162
I think those of us not working on free-to-play games

561
00:26:42,162 --> 00:26:43,845
can think of this too as a way of addressing

562
00:26:43,845 --> 00:26:44,806
your player base.

563
00:26:44,806 --> 00:26:46,529
You know, thinking, are we spending too much time

564
00:26:46,529 --> 00:26:47,931
on the people who've been playing for 30 hours

565
00:26:47,931 --> 00:26:49,674
and not enough on most of the players

566
00:26:49,674 --> 00:26:50,736
who aren't gonna get that far?

567
00:26:51,276 --> 00:26:53,897
I think you can easily easily extrapolate this to other types of games.

568
00:26:53,897 --> 00:26:57,179
Next up, we have Christina Norman.

569
00:26:57,179 --> 00:27:00,801
She was a programmer and then a designer at Bioware on the Mass Effect series

570
00:27:00,801 --> 00:27:04,742
and now works on that little other free to play game League of Legends.

571
00:27:04,742 --> 00:27:07,744
And she's here to say the problem you think you have,

572
00:27:07,744 --> 00:27:09,885
well, maybe it's not actually a problem at all.

573
00:27:09,885 --> 00:27:11,566
I give you Christina Norman.

574
00:27:11,566 --> 00:27:11,786
Hello, hello.

575
00:27:20,841 --> 00:27:26,733
So today I want to convince you guys to willingly embrace radical constraints.

576
00:27:28,688 --> 00:27:31,470
Now, designers generally hate constraints.

577
00:27:31,470 --> 00:27:34,191
We look at constraints as restrictions on what we can do.

578
00:27:34,191 --> 00:27:35,892
And who wants to be restricted?

579
00:27:35,892 --> 00:27:38,454
We want to do whatever we want to do.

580
00:27:38,454 --> 00:27:43,216
But constraints can also really help us focus our creativity.

581
00:27:43,216 --> 00:27:45,417
I think we all have stories of situations

582
00:27:45,417 --> 00:27:48,099
where we've been working under the absolutely harshest

583
00:27:48,099 --> 00:27:50,900
restrictions, and we've done incredible things.

584
00:27:50,900 --> 00:27:54,982
Constraints can really inspire us to solve hard problems

585
00:27:54,982 --> 00:27:57,664
and innovate as designers when we accept them.

586
00:27:58,732 --> 00:28:02,575
So I'm gonna take you through three constraint scenarios

587
00:28:02,575 --> 00:28:05,177
and I'm gonna introduce a constraints framework to you

588
00:28:05,177 --> 00:28:09,160
and show you how I solve two impossible problems solving it.

589
00:28:09,160 --> 00:28:11,642
Whoops.

590
00:28:11,642 --> 00:28:13,944
And, ah, why is Shepard a panda?

591
00:28:13,944 --> 00:28:14,464
Wait a second.

592
00:28:14,464 --> 00:28:14,864
Okay, we got this.

593
00:28:18,899 --> 00:28:19,679
There we go.

594
00:28:19,679 --> 00:28:23,500
And I will be using industry standard three panda notation,

595
00:28:23,500 --> 00:28:25,421
which I believe originated at NYU,

596
00:28:25,421 --> 00:28:29,462
to indicate how the team felt through all of this,

597
00:28:29,462 --> 00:28:32,423
because changing constraints can be really stressful.

598
00:28:32,423 --> 00:28:35,244
So throughout this, when you see a happy panda,

599
00:28:35,244 --> 00:28:38,264
that's a developer who is working contentedly

600
00:28:38,264 --> 00:28:39,185
within constraints.

601
00:28:39,685 --> 00:28:42,385
When you see a sad panda, that's a developer

602
00:28:42,385 --> 00:28:45,106
who is feeling frustrated and restricted by constraints.

603
00:28:45,106 --> 00:28:48,026
And when you see a sneaky panda, that's

604
00:28:48,026 --> 00:28:51,027
a developer who is ignoring constraints to solve problems.

605
00:28:51,027 --> 00:28:55,747
And the size of the panda indicates the level of impact.

606
00:28:55,747 --> 00:29:00,048
So let's start off by going through the story of Mass

607
00:29:00,048 --> 00:29:00,968
Effect 1.

608
00:29:00,968 --> 00:29:04,549
Now, Mass Effect 1 started like all possible games

609
00:29:04,549 --> 00:29:06,749
with a blank slate.

610
00:29:06,749 --> 00:29:08,650
It really could have been anything.

611
00:29:09,452 --> 00:29:12,714
For example, we could have made it a pure dating sim.

612
00:29:12,714 --> 00:29:15,036
And there's probably an alternate universe out there

613
00:29:15,036 --> 00:29:18,278
where we did that, and it's probably a pretty cool universe.

614
00:29:18,278 --> 00:29:22,981
But we wanted to focus on other aspects as well.

615
00:29:22,981 --> 00:29:26,964
So we wanted it to be a epic space opera RPG

616
00:29:26,964 --> 00:29:29,446
in which you could explore the galaxy,

617
00:29:29,446 --> 00:29:32,608
save the universe, command an elite squad of superheroes,

618
00:29:32,608 --> 00:29:33,989
you know, pretty basic stuff.

619
00:29:33,989 --> 00:29:34,309
And...

620
00:29:36,331 --> 00:29:41,675
We had a schedule and a budget, so as we went through that initial concepting phase,

621
00:29:41,675 --> 00:29:43,476
we realized we had to get specific.

622
00:29:43,476 --> 00:29:48,099
So we fleshed out the plot, we figured out who the characters were going to be,

623
00:29:48,099 --> 00:29:53,643
we identified the RPG rules, we figured out key systems for conversations and gameplay

624
00:29:53,643 --> 00:29:56,966
that would make the game really great, and we made some tough calls.

625
00:29:57,871 --> 00:30:01,435
Then we prototype key systems, verifying that they were both

626
00:30:01,435 --> 00:30:03,338
possible and valuable.

627
00:30:03,338 --> 00:30:05,961
It was becoming more and more clear to us as a team what

628
00:30:05,961 --> 00:30:08,124
Mass Effect would be and what it wouldn't be.

629
00:30:09,274 --> 00:30:13,376
Then E3 happened and we had to show Mass Effect to the world.

630
00:30:13,376 --> 00:30:16,077
So we developed this vertical slice

631
00:30:16,077 --> 00:30:18,258
that would capture all the key experiences

632
00:30:18,258 --> 00:30:19,999
that players would have in Mass Effect,

633
00:30:19,999 --> 00:30:23,181
like explorations, cinematic conversations,

634
00:30:23,181 --> 00:30:25,102
and intense squad combat.

635
00:30:25,102 --> 00:30:28,223
This was really hard, but the team gave it their all.

636
00:30:28,223 --> 00:30:30,685
And overall, we were really happy with the results

637
00:30:30,685 --> 00:30:31,945
and players were excited.

638
00:30:33,361 --> 00:30:40,045
But then as we set out to realize this vision across the entire game, we encountered huge problems executing at scale.

639
00:30:40,045 --> 00:30:45,548
Like most developers, our E3 demo was visionary but it wasn't real.

640
00:30:45,548 --> 00:30:49,270
And as we tried to create real experiences at a galactic scale...

641
00:30:49,691 --> 00:30:55,098
we ran into horrendous technical problems with our engine, with our workflow.

642
00:30:55,098 --> 00:30:57,021
They kept slowing us down.

643
00:30:57,021 --> 00:31:02,148
And now for the first time as a team, we collectively felt we were being constrained in a way

644
00:31:02,148 --> 00:31:05,232
that was taking all of us away from the game we wanted it to be.

645
00:31:06,595 --> 00:31:09,236
And then it got worse.

646
00:31:09,236 --> 00:31:11,837
As we got closer and closer to our ship date,

647
00:31:11,837 --> 00:31:14,698
we realized that we were not trending well.

648
00:31:14,698 --> 00:31:16,719
So we started cutting features.

649
00:31:16,719 --> 00:31:20,120
We started cutting entire planets from the game.

650
00:31:20,120 --> 00:31:22,861
We had to not just make new content,

651
00:31:22,861 --> 00:31:25,522
but we had to rebuild our existing content and systems

652
00:31:25,522 --> 00:31:27,142
to make them more efficient.

653
00:31:27,142 --> 00:31:28,803
All of this was slowing us down,

654
00:31:28,803 --> 00:31:31,604
and we felt like Mass Effect was slipping away.

655
00:31:32,244 --> 00:31:36,891
So we crunched, because that solves all problems, right guys?

656
00:31:36,891 --> 00:31:40,355
Through force of will, talent, focus, and Red Bull,

657
00:31:40,355 --> 00:31:44,641
we dragged Mass Effect back closer to where we wanted it to be,

658
00:31:44,641 --> 00:31:48,106
but the cost on the team was really, really high.

659
00:31:49,272 --> 00:31:51,353
But in the end, despite all this adversity,

660
00:31:51,353 --> 00:31:54,475
we shipped Mass Effect and it was awesome

661
00:31:54,475 --> 00:31:55,675
and players loved it.

662
00:31:55,675 --> 00:31:59,257
It wasn't exactly what we'd wanted it to be.

663
00:31:59,257 --> 00:32:02,159
It's getting outside of that original space

664
00:32:02,159 --> 00:32:03,439
we wanted it to be in,

665
00:32:03,439 --> 00:32:05,640
but it was definitely a great game.

666
00:32:07,497 --> 00:32:10,999
And reflecting on that journey from Blank Slate to Mass Effect,

667
00:32:10,999 --> 00:32:15,382
I started to see how constraints were a roadmap for our progress.

668
00:32:15,382 --> 00:32:20,366
And I started wondering if we could use them to help get the team

669
00:32:20,366 --> 00:32:22,647
pointed towards better games with fewer sad pandas.

670
00:32:22,647 --> 00:32:25,389
And we all wanted Mass Effect 2 to be a better game.

671
00:32:25,389 --> 00:32:29,091
We wanted to fix all the problems with the first one.

672
00:32:29,091 --> 00:32:31,153
We wanted it to be refined.

673
00:32:31,153 --> 00:32:33,614
We wanted it to be polished.

674
00:32:33,614 --> 00:32:37,116
And we wanted the team to not be miserable, sad pandas.

675
00:32:38,578 --> 00:32:41,761
So when we started with that blank slate of Mass Effect 2,

676
00:32:41,761 --> 00:32:45,123
we knew that the first thing we had to do

677
00:32:45,123 --> 00:32:46,965
was figure out how we were gonna address

678
00:32:46,965 --> 00:32:48,246
those problems from Mass Effect.

679
00:32:48,246 --> 00:32:52,009
And inventory was one of those top of mind problems.

680
00:32:52,009 --> 00:32:53,390
For those of you who didn't play,

681
00:32:53,390 --> 00:32:55,952
Mass Effect's inventory was slow, it was clunky,

682
00:32:55,952 --> 00:32:58,394
and you had to interact with it constantly.

683
00:32:58,394 --> 00:33:02,898
It was universally disliked, so it was a clear must fix.

684
00:33:04,038 --> 00:33:06,500
Thus, one of the constraints we established early on

685
00:33:06,500 --> 00:33:10,422
was that we were gonna have a good inventory system.

686
00:33:10,422 --> 00:33:13,424
And we designed a great inventory system,

687
00:33:13,424 --> 00:33:15,866
but then what we found was,

688
00:33:15,866 --> 00:33:18,788
as we were rebuilding our UI pipeline

689
00:33:18,788 --> 00:33:22,050
and finding that we had some programmers who quit

690
00:33:22,050 --> 00:33:24,692
and we couldn't hire some other programmers,

691
00:33:24,692 --> 00:33:26,593
things were not trending well.

692
00:33:26,593 --> 00:33:29,335
It became clear that the inventory we wanted to build

693
00:33:29,335 --> 00:33:31,456
for Mass Effect 2 was not possible.

694
00:33:32,517 --> 00:33:35,182
So we designed a lower scope inventory, right?

695
00:33:35,182 --> 00:33:37,506
But the problem was that wasn't possible either.

696
00:33:37,506 --> 00:33:40,532
Our UI problems were that bad.

697
00:33:40,532 --> 00:33:41,835
So we changed our approach.

698
00:33:43,182 --> 00:33:46,223
We designed a possible inventory system,

699
00:33:46,223 --> 00:33:50,105
but the problem now was it wasn't really very good,

700
00:33:50,105 --> 00:33:51,966
and to make it possible,

701
00:33:51,966 --> 00:33:54,407
we knew we'd have to cut some big things from the game.

702
00:33:54,407 --> 00:33:56,988
And those things we were gonna have to cut

703
00:33:56,988 --> 00:33:58,329
were pretty awesome.

704
00:33:58,329 --> 00:33:59,990
This felt really bad,

705
00:33:59,990 --> 00:34:03,191
and no one was happy with the situation.

706
00:34:03,191 --> 00:34:04,492
So then I had an idea.

707
00:34:04,492 --> 00:34:06,693
Why don't we just cut the inventory itself?

708
00:34:06,693 --> 00:34:09,515
It seemed like it was the source of all the problems.

709
00:34:10,651 --> 00:34:15,015
And I proposed this idea to the team and they were confused.

710
00:34:15,015 --> 00:34:19,478
Everyone knows Mass Effect was a Bioware RPG

711
00:34:19,478 --> 00:34:22,641
and Bioware RPGs have inventories

712
00:34:22,641 --> 00:34:24,483
and wasn't the whole point to make sure

713
00:34:24,483 --> 00:34:25,964
that we had a good inventory?

714
00:34:25,964 --> 00:34:27,185
Wasn't that what we were setting out to do

715
00:34:27,185 --> 00:34:28,366
in the first place?

716
00:34:29,520 --> 00:34:31,802
So I reframed the problem and I said,

717
00:34:31,802 --> 00:34:34,503
I don't think we really need a good inventory system.

718
00:34:34,503 --> 00:34:36,765
The problem was we had a bad one.

719
00:34:36,765 --> 00:34:38,946
So if we don't have a bad inventory,

720
00:34:38,946 --> 00:34:41,428
haven't we really solved that original problem?

721
00:34:41,428 --> 00:34:44,089
I didn't convince the team at this point,

722
00:34:44,089 --> 00:34:45,950
but I opened their minds up a bit

723
00:34:45,950 --> 00:34:48,292
to see that maybe there'd be another way.

724
00:34:49,312 --> 00:34:50,473
But people were skeptical.

725
00:34:50,473 --> 00:34:53,936
What would Mass Effect even look like without an inventory?

726
00:34:53,936 --> 00:34:55,177
Would it even be an RPG?

727
00:34:55,177 --> 00:34:56,698
Would it be fun?

728
00:34:56,698 --> 00:34:59,160
These were important questions to answer.

729
00:34:59,160 --> 00:35:02,042
So the design team dug in really deep,

730
00:35:02,042 --> 00:35:04,464
deconstructing why we needed an inventory

731
00:35:04,464 --> 00:35:05,604
in the first place,

732
00:35:05,604 --> 00:35:07,626
and identifying the problems we'd have to solve

733
00:35:07,626 --> 00:35:09,487
if we removed it.

734
00:35:09,487 --> 00:35:12,990
One by one, we proposed solutions to those problems

735
00:35:12,990 --> 00:35:14,691
and built confidence in the new direction

736
00:35:14,691 --> 00:35:16,593
until we had buy-in from the team.

737
00:35:17,763 --> 00:35:20,946
And in the end, Mass Effect 2 didn't have an inventory,

738
00:35:20,946 --> 00:35:22,567
and it was a much better game.

739
00:35:22,567 --> 00:35:24,749
By going out of our comfort zone,

740
00:35:24,749 --> 00:35:26,871
we'd solved an impossible problem

741
00:35:26,871 --> 00:35:29,073
and unlocked a new way of thinking about things

742
00:35:29,073 --> 00:35:31,035
that helped lead us to other changes

743
00:35:31,035 --> 00:35:34,318
that made Mass Effect more focused and polished.

744
00:35:35,613 --> 00:35:38,335
And reflecting on that experience,

745
00:35:38,335 --> 00:35:39,936
I wanted to generalize this.

746
00:35:39,936 --> 00:35:41,116
Like, was this just a fluke?

747
00:35:41,116 --> 00:35:44,218
Had we got lucky with a random idea?

748
00:35:44,218 --> 00:35:45,899
So I thought about the whole process

749
00:35:45,899 --> 00:35:48,160
and what had happened and tried to generalize it.

750
00:35:49,575 --> 00:35:53,177
So first, the thing I saw is that we had to identify

751
00:35:53,177 --> 00:35:55,078
that we had an impossible problem.

752
00:35:55,078 --> 00:35:58,159
Teams don't like to admit that things are impossible.

753
00:35:58,159 --> 00:35:59,920
They don't like to acknowledge being blocked.

754
00:35:59,920 --> 00:36:02,841
They wanna work harder and realize their original vision.

755
00:36:02,841 --> 00:36:05,802
But when repeated attempts to solve problems

756
00:36:05,802 --> 00:36:07,783
creatively and analytically fail,

757
00:36:07,783 --> 00:36:09,604
it's important to acknowledge

758
00:36:09,604 --> 00:36:12,285
that you are not trending towards success.

759
00:36:12,285 --> 00:36:14,366
This helps open up the team's mind

760
00:36:14,366 --> 00:36:16,686
so they're willing to look at a different approach.

761
00:36:17,973 --> 00:36:19,815
Then you need to ideate.

762
00:36:19,815 --> 00:36:22,038
Clearly, at this creative ideation stage,

763
00:36:22,038 --> 00:36:23,760
you must ignore constraints,

764
00:36:23,760 --> 00:36:27,545
and you must not allow analysis to shoot down ideas.

765
00:36:27,545 --> 00:36:29,767
There are no buzzkill pandas at this zone.

766
00:36:31,125 --> 00:36:34,786
Dangerous ideas must be allowed and even encouraged.

767
00:36:34,786 --> 00:36:38,688
But then, as you go into the reframing stage,

768
00:36:38,688 --> 00:36:41,789
you find a way to reframe those original constraints

769
00:36:41,789 --> 00:36:44,451
in a way that allows your solution to be possible.

770
00:36:44,451 --> 00:36:48,052
And you identify all the issues that are going to come about

771
00:36:48,052 --> 00:36:49,373
because there will be issues.

772
00:36:49,373 --> 00:36:51,574
You probably had good reasons why those constraints

773
00:36:51,574 --> 00:36:52,814
were there in the first place.

774
00:36:53,695 --> 00:36:55,676
Then you have to solve those issues.

775
00:36:55,676 --> 00:36:58,398
One by one, you work through them.

776
00:36:58,398 --> 00:37:00,920
You prioritize and you solve quickly.

777
00:37:00,920 --> 00:37:03,542
Your goal at this point is to determine

778
00:37:03,542 --> 00:37:05,063
if this is a viable direction,

779
00:37:05,063 --> 00:37:06,624
to build buy-in from the team.

780
00:37:06,624 --> 00:37:09,386
You are not building production code or content

781
00:37:09,386 --> 00:37:11,567
because you don't know if this is going to work out.

782
00:37:12,982 --> 00:37:15,084
Then lastly, you reintegrate.

783
00:37:15,084 --> 00:37:19,608
This process must end with a cohesive, whole vision

784
00:37:19,608 --> 00:37:22,270
for where the product is going, and clear constraints

785
00:37:22,270 --> 00:37:24,592
that the team can accept and work happily in.

786
00:37:24,592 --> 00:37:27,574
That's how you end up with happy pandas working

787
00:37:27,574 --> 00:37:28,795
within new constraints.

788
00:37:28,795 --> 00:37:32,398
So this looked great on paper, but to figure out

789
00:37:32,398 --> 00:37:35,380
if this actually worked, I needed

790
00:37:35,380 --> 00:37:37,162
to solve another impossible problem.

791
00:37:37,162 --> 00:37:39,744
But luckily, Game Dev, those happen every week.

792
00:37:41,268 --> 00:37:43,629
So when we moved into Mass Effect 3,

793
00:37:43,629 --> 00:37:45,511
we knew we wanted to do something big.

794
00:37:45,511 --> 00:37:48,173
Mass Effect 2 had been a really big success,

795
00:37:48,173 --> 00:37:49,794
so we wanted to do something big

796
00:37:49,794 --> 00:37:51,775
to make it more than Mass Effect 2.

797
00:37:51,775 --> 00:37:54,437
And multiplayer was big.

798
00:37:54,437 --> 00:37:56,758
We'd actually always wanted to have multiplayer

799
00:37:56,758 --> 00:37:59,020
in Mass Effect, but we hadn't had the time

800
00:37:59,020 --> 00:38:00,701
or resources to do it.

801
00:38:00,701 --> 00:38:03,483
It was pretty scary to add this on in the third game,

802
00:38:03,483 --> 00:38:06,085
and the team was nervous, but they were also excited

803
00:38:06,085 --> 00:38:07,406
by this ambitious goal.

804
00:38:08,473 --> 00:38:09,954
So then we did some research,

805
00:38:09,954 --> 00:38:12,774
and that research proved very troubling.

806
00:38:12,774 --> 00:38:15,075
All of our data and surveys said that multiplayer

807
00:38:15,075 --> 00:38:16,835
was a winner-take-all market

808
00:38:16,835 --> 00:38:19,256
that was dominated by big PvP games.

809
00:38:19,256 --> 00:38:22,357
Even worse, when we surveyed Bioware players,

810
00:38:22,357 --> 00:38:25,237
we found out they had low engagement in multiplayer,

811
00:38:25,237 --> 00:38:27,158
and they really weren't that excited

812
00:38:27,158 --> 00:38:28,978
by the idea of a multiplayer Mass Effect.

813
00:38:28,978 --> 00:38:30,699
Seriously, like, the most common response is,

814
00:38:30,699 --> 00:38:32,759
can you just make more single-player levels, please?

815
00:38:34,222 --> 00:38:37,323
So to make successful high-quality multiplayer,

816
00:38:37,323 --> 00:38:40,344
we knew we had to build a different kind of multiplayer,

817
00:38:40,344 --> 00:38:41,624
Bioware multiplayer.

818
00:38:41,624 --> 00:38:45,446
And that meant a co-op game that had everything

819
00:38:45,446 --> 00:38:47,126
that Bioware players love,

820
00:38:47,126 --> 00:38:51,268
like an exclusive multiplayer story,

821
00:38:51,268 --> 00:38:52,508
co-op level mechanics,

822
00:38:52,508 --> 00:38:55,709
and levels that you couldn't choose solo.

823
00:38:55,709 --> 00:38:58,190
We needed new enemies, powers, and weapons,

824
00:38:58,190 --> 00:39:00,671
content you could only access in multiplayer.

825
00:39:01,609 --> 00:39:08,434
Plus, we needed social network integration, so recruiting your friends to play would be really easy.

826
00:39:08,434 --> 00:39:14,819
And this was basically the scope of an entirely new game, and it was a pretty cool concept for a game,

827
00:39:14,819 --> 00:39:18,902
but it wasn't feasible Mass Effect 3 multiplayer.

828
00:39:18,902 --> 00:39:23,345
We were back with an impossible problem and a great chance to test the framework.

829
00:39:24,775 --> 00:39:31,624
So, first of all, we just had to acknowledge that the plan we had for multiplayer was not going to work.

830
00:39:31,624 --> 00:39:38,233
The scope was too high to ship, even though we had planned on dedicating a pretty sizable dedicated multiplayer team.

831
00:39:39,258 --> 00:39:42,401
Then we ideated to find an alternate approach.

832
00:39:42,401 --> 00:39:46,826
And what we kind of landed on was our base assumption

833
00:39:46,826 --> 00:39:50,350
that players would not want to play Mass Effect multiplayer.

834
00:39:50,350 --> 00:39:54,634
What if co-op plus Mass Effect's gameplay was super fun?

835
00:39:54,634 --> 00:39:56,797
How would that change the situation?

836
00:39:56,797 --> 00:40:00,621
Then we reframed our original constraints.

837
00:40:01,766 --> 00:40:04,627
we would make a game with co-op Mass Effect gameplay

838
00:40:04,627 --> 00:40:06,547
that was really fun, and then we'd

839
00:40:06,547 --> 00:40:08,668
identify the problems we'd still need

840
00:40:08,668 --> 00:40:12,409
to solve to make it a great multiplayer for BioWare players.

841
00:40:12,409 --> 00:40:15,670
Then we solved those problems.

842
00:40:15,670 --> 00:40:18,311
First, we validated our original assumption

843
00:40:18,311 --> 00:40:21,992
by doing a horde mode prototype of Mass Effect's multiplayer

844
00:40:21,992 --> 00:40:23,232
to verify it was fun.

845
00:40:24,165 --> 00:40:26,466
We improved it by adding on objectives,

846
00:40:26,466 --> 00:40:29,067
limited powers, and a high difficulty.

847
00:40:29,067 --> 00:40:31,808
Then we identified that we needed additional stickiness

848
00:40:31,808 --> 00:40:34,749
to keep players coming in and to entice them

849
00:40:34,749 --> 00:40:37,070
to come in in the first place.

850
00:40:37,070 --> 00:40:40,531
So we fleshed out some pretty intense progression systems.

851
00:40:40,531 --> 00:40:44,473
And in the end, with a strong co-op horde mode demo

852
00:40:44,473 --> 00:40:48,354
that was really fun, and that updated vision,

853
00:40:48,354 --> 00:40:50,915
we got buy-in from the team and moved forward

854
00:40:50,915 --> 00:40:52,436
with Mass Effect's multiplayer.

855
00:40:53,258 --> 00:40:55,761
Now, about this time I actually left Bioware,

856
00:40:55,761 --> 00:40:59,685
but the multiplayer team took that prototype

857
00:40:59,685 --> 00:41:02,628
and they built it out to be Mass Effect 3's multiplayer

858
00:41:02,628 --> 00:41:04,370
and they did an amazing job.

859
00:41:04,370 --> 00:41:07,653
That same team has now gone on to build Andromeda

860
00:41:07,653 --> 00:41:09,535
and I cannot wait to check it out.

861
00:41:11,139 --> 00:41:14,461
And just to be clear, we did what we set out to do.

862
00:41:14,461 --> 00:41:18,324
We made multiplayer that Bioware players wanted to play.

863
00:41:18,324 --> 00:41:21,026
In fact, they wanted to play it so much,

864
00:41:21,026 --> 00:41:23,007
they spent more time in multiplayer

865
00:41:23,007 --> 00:41:24,428
than they did in single player.

866
00:41:24,428 --> 00:41:29,431
For the third game in a primarily single player RPG franchise,

867
00:41:29,431 --> 00:41:32,453
that was success beyond what we'd ever imagined.

868
00:41:34,540 --> 00:41:38,003
So to kind of sum up, I really want to encourage you guys,

869
00:41:38,003 --> 00:41:41,765
when your teams get blocked, take a step back,

870
00:41:41,765 --> 00:41:43,667
consider adjusting your approach

871
00:41:43,667 --> 00:41:45,588
and embrace radical constraints.

872
00:41:45,588 --> 00:41:46,048
Thank you.

873
00:41:54,637 --> 00:41:57,419
Thank you, Christina.

874
00:41:57,419 --> 00:42:00,822
So moving on here to our next speaker.

875
00:42:00,822 --> 00:42:04,525
Our next speaker is not Christina Norman.

876
00:42:05,386 --> 00:42:08,046
is Hal Barwood.

877
00:42:08,046 --> 00:42:10,307
He is somewhat special in that he's

878
00:42:10,307 --> 00:42:12,887
one of the main inspirations behind this session.

879
00:42:12,887 --> 00:42:16,048
Years ago, he worked on probably the most beloved Indiana Jones

880
00:42:16,048 --> 00:42:20,369
games of all time, and also was an illustrious game design

881
00:42:20,369 --> 00:42:23,350
speaker at GDC for many years that inspired me

882
00:42:23,350 --> 00:42:25,370
in my first years coming here, and actually worked

883
00:42:25,370 --> 00:42:28,150
on a first framework of establishing rules for game

884
00:42:28,150 --> 00:42:30,751
design called the 400 Project.

885
00:42:30,751 --> 00:42:33,492
And he's here today to talk a little bit about that.

886
00:42:33,932 --> 00:42:36,734
and what went right and what went wrong with that,

887
00:42:36,734 --> 00:42:37,655
and also some other stuff.

888
00:42:37,655 --> 00:42:38,896
I give you Hal Barwood.

889
00:42:38,896 --> 00:42:39,056
Thanks.

890
00:42:39,056 --> 00:42:39,196
Hi there.

891
00:42:39,196 --> 00:42:45,081
Let's look at some history.

892
00:42:54,113 --> 00:43:00,056
I delivered the first talk on game design rules at GDC 16 years ago in 2001.

893
00:43:00,056 --> 00:43:01,396
It was called For the 400.

894
00:43:01,396 --> 00:43:05,718
I had observed that most arts have a lot of rules,

895
00:43:05,718 --> 00:43:08,199
and the practitioners need them and use them

896
00:43:08,199 --> 00:43:10,820
in order to be able to cope with the difficulties of their work.

897
00:43:10,820 --> 00:43:14,682
But I also noticed that game designers did not seem to participate.

898
00:43:14,682 --> 00:43:16,503
And I wondered, why not?

899
00:43:17,468 --> 00:43:22,071
Well, were games just too new back then to have developed any rules?

900
00:43:22,071 --> 00:43:26,013
Are we guided by formal principles instead, as some have advocated?

901
00:43:26,013 --> 00:43:29,595
Or is it just the libertarian streak in game designers that says,

902
00:43:29,595 --> 00:43:30,916
we don't need no stinking rules?

903
00:43:30,916 --> 00:43:33,897
Well, I thought that rules must exist.

904
00:43:33,897 --> 00:43:36,999
But I thought they were mostly unstated.

905
00:43:37,557 --> 00:43:41,099
They were intuitive, implicit, foggy, vague, and therefore,

906
00:43:41,099 --> 00:43:41,900
very unreliable.

907
00:43:41,900 --> 00:43:43,781
And I wanted to change that.

908
00:43:43,781 --> 00:43:46,683
And when I look back, I think I was on the right track.

909
00:43:46,683 --> 00:43:50,665
Because here we are, 16 years later, still identifying rules

910
00:43:50,665 --> 00:43:53,067
and advocating for their use.

911
00:43:53,067 --> 00:43:55,989
Noah Falstein and I did a couple of follow-up talks at

912
00:43:55,989 --> 00:43:59,851
GDC, and we started the 400 Project, inviting developers

913
00:43:59,851 --> 00:44:02,553
to come to us with rules, which we would then publish up.

914
00:44:03,513 --> 00:44:09,878
We compiled and collected more than a hundred of these before we moved on to other things.

915
00:44:09,878 --> 00:44:14,362
Let's look at some representatives of these rules that are typical.

916
00:44:15,190 --> 00:44:16,811
Let the player turn the game off.

917
00:44:16,811 --> 00:44:20,893
Bad save game systems cause players to repeatedly trudge

918
00:44:20,893 --> 00:44:23,154
through vast tracts of a game they can't figure out.

919
00:44:23,154 --> 00:44:25,836
They learn to hate the developer, and they quit.

920
00:44:25,836 --> 00:44:28,157
A good save game system lets you stop and start

921
00:44:28,157 --> 00:44:30,078
wherever you want.

922
00:44:30,078 --> 00:44:32,959
If you add a small amount of randomness to AI calcs, the

923
00:44:32,959 --> 00:44:35,941
stupid NPCs that are running around may give you the

924
00:44:35,941 --> 00:44:37,622
illusion of intelligence.

925
00:44:37,622 --> 00:44:39,683
And things that look alike should behave alike.

926
00:44:41,084 --> 00:44:45,206
The items that an avatar can pick up and use should have a graphic emphasis over and above

927
00:44:45,206 --> 00:44:51,210
mere decor. Well, these are good rules. These, the ones I've just discussed, are very much

928
00:44:51,210 --> 00:44:57,333
like the rest of them. But they're small rules. They're minor. It's hard to believe that game

929
00:44:57,333 --> 00:45:02,116
designers would be guided by rules like this in their thought processes. And I was wondering

930
00:45:02,116 --> 00:45:06,499
why in all the hundred rules we got, we didn't uncover anything more important or deeper.

931
00:45:07,382 --> 00:45:08,943
And I think there are a couple of reasons.

932
00:45:08,943 --> 00:45:11,906
Deep rules are very hard to articulate.

933
00:45:11,906 --> 00:45:14,488
And I think that there's a faction of game designers that

934
00:45:14,488 --> 00:45:16,610
feel that resorting to rules is to make

935
00:45:16,610 --> 00:45:17,631
use of shallow tricks.

936
00:45:18,668 --> 00:45:22,492
Well, I think that rules are the summation of prior experience

937
00:45:22,492 --> 00:45:23,873
and carry with them great wisdom.

938
00:45:23,873 --> 00:45:28,478
And the important rules are big rules, rules that hold sway,

939
00:45:28,478 --> 00:45:31,301
rules that actually can become part of your guidebook

940
00:45:31,301 --> 00:45:33,283
for how you go about your work.

941
00:45:33,283 --> 00:45:34,805
I want to discuss one such rule today.

942
00:45:34,805 --> 00:45:37,427
It's one of mine.

943
00:45:37,427 --> 00:45:38,869
It's personify your problems.

944
00:45:39,833 --> 00:45:43,814
And what it means is to use characters to solve design difficulties.

945
00:45:43,814 --> 00:45:48,176
When you have a problem in front of you that might be solved mechanically,

946
00:45:48,176 --> 00:45:52,117
instead, see if you can get an NPC to take on that job.

947
00:45:52,117 --> 00:45:54,517
Well, this is fundamental to the sort of games that I like to play

948
00:45:54,517 --> 00:45:56,558
that involve lots of character interaction,

949
00:45:56,558 --> 00:46:02,039
a certain amount of righteous combat, and traversal and exploration.

950
00:46:02,039 --> 00:46:05,540
Well, character interaction, combat, exploration,

951
00:46:05,540 --> 00:46:07,441
this is the domain of narrative games.

952
00:46:08,483 --> 00:46:13,105
They don't cover the waterfront of game design, but they cut a broad swath through it.

953
00:46:13,105 --> 00:46:17,366
And I confess, the rule originates with my career as a screenwriter.

954
00:46:17,366 --> 00:46:22,448
Let's see how the rule applies to an old movie that I worked on, Close Encounters of the

955
00:46:22,448 --> 00:46:23,668
Third Kind.

956
00:46:23,668 --> 00:46:26,770
Steve Spielberg wanted his ending to be an awesome spectacle.

957
00:46:26,770 --> 00:46:31,191
The problem in a movie is that awesomeness only goes so far.

958
00:46:31,191 --> 00:46:31,891
It's very dry.

959
00:46:33,222 --> 00:46:37,106
Bearing that in mind, when Matthew Robbins and I revised Steve's script, we invented

960
00:46:37,106 --> 00:46:38,247
Little Barry.

961
00:46:38,247 --> 00:46:41,892
We got him abducted by aliens in the first act, and we delivered him to his mother's

962
00:46:41,892 --> 00:46:46,056
arms in the finale in order to give that awesomeness some emotional heft.

963
00:46:47,694 --> 00:46:52,036
When Matthew's in my movie, Dragonslayer, it's all about a romp and stomp and very scary

964
00:46:52,036 --> 00:46:52,396
dragon.

965
00:46:52,396 --> 00:46:56,878
But the dragon is an animal, a force of nature, and not a dramatic villain.

966
00:46:56,878 --> 00:47:02,761
So we invented creepy King Cassiodorus and his hateful sacrificial lottery that he uses

967
00:47:02,761 --> 00:47:05,863
to appease the dragon to give the movie dramatic structure.

968
00:47:05,863 --> 00:47:10,485
So does that mean that what I'm talking about is just storytelling?

969
00:47:10,485 --> 00:47:10,925
Not at all.

970
00:47:12,020 --> 00:47:14,862
Show don't tell in movies, which is a perfectly fine principle,

971
00:47:14,862 --> 00:47:17,724
becomes play don't show when you come to games.

972
00:47:17,724 --> 00:47:19,746
So when my rule moves to the world of games,

973
00:47:19,746 --> 00:47:23,068
it's all about design, how to weld the story and the game

974
00:47:23,068 --> 00:47:23,569
play together.

975
00:47:23,569 --> 00:47:24,869
Let's look at some examples.

976
00:47:24,869 --> 00:47:29,533
Here's one, how to keep danger alive before it arrives.

977
00:47:30,475 --> 00:47:32,717
In my old adventure game, Fate of Atlantis,

978
00:47:32,717 --> 00:47:35,238
the player's gonna spend hours running around

979
00:47:35,238 --> 00:47:37,339
before you ever arrive at the mysterious lost city.

980
00:47:37,339 --> 00:47:41,201
So we invented a companion for Indy, Sophia Hapgood.

981
00:47:41,201 --> 00:47:43,863
And we outfitted her with a necklace

982
00:47:43,863 --> 00:47:44,763
that comes from that city

983
00:47:44,763 --> 00:47:48,265
that carries with it a supernatural, unhealthy aura.

984
00:47:48,265 --> 00:47:51,787
Indy's a little doubtful that she's turned into a psychic,

985
00:47:51,787 --> 00:47:53,768
but we learn right away

986
00:47:53,768 --> 00:47:55,729
that her claims are not entirely imaginary.

987
00:47:56,787 --> 00:48:01,768
and a series of spooky puzzles involving her stand in for the mystery of the city until

988
00:48:01,768 --> 00:48:08,150
we actually arrive there. Well, here's a different kind of problem. Star Wars items and the poverty

989
00:48:08,150 --> 00:48:14,511
thereof. A while ago, I made a little replayable action-adventure game called Yoda Stories.

990
00:48:14,511 --> 00:48:18,472
There are 15 scenarios. There are hundreds of ways to put them together. You can go through

991
00:48:18,472 --> 00:48:19,853
it each time in less than an hour.

992
00:48:20,789 --> 00:48:23,171
When we made it, we didn't know how to categorize this,

993
00:48:23,171 --> 00:48:25,133
but we now just call these things casual games.

994
00:48:25,133 --> 00:48:27,215
And it's just a little applet on your desk.

995
00:48:27,215 --> 00:48:31,219
But the problem is that progress through a game like this

996
00:48:31,219 --> 00:48:33,360
is gated by a series of puzzle chains.

997
00:48:33,360 --> 00:48:35,903
And we scoured the Star Wars Bible,

998
00:48:35,903 --> 00:48:39,186
and we found very few useful keys and tools.

999
00:48:39,186 --> 00:48:41,588
You're looking at a lot of them right here.

1000
00:48:41,588 --> 00:48:44,150
What would you do with a Lomite crystal?

1001
00:48:44,150 --> 00:48:46,212
Well, we invented a new puzzle type

1002
00:48:46,212 --> 00:48:47,673
to go along with keys and tools.

1003
00:48:47,982 --> 00:48:53,287
and tools, we invented valuables, items that only have human meaning.

1004
00:48:53,287 --> 00:48:58,812
So if you're a super-deformed Boba Fett and you demand a Lomite crystal, you super-deformed

1005
00:48:58,812 --> 00:49:02,875
Luke Skywalker better go and get one if you want to advance the action.

1006
00:49:02,875 --> 00:49:10,322
This idea allowed us to create dozens of transactional puzzles involving lots of dialogue and characters

1007
00:49:10,322 --> 00:49:13,244
to warm this little game up.

1008
00:49:13,244 --> 00:49:15,826
Now a slightly larger question is how do you take

1009
00:49:16,977 --> 00:49:22,883
a Jones story, which originated in film, and translate that into the world of games.

1010
00:49:22,883 --> 00:49:27,267
Jones stories always take place in an exaggerated version of the here and now.

1011
00:49:27,267 --> 00:49:29,609
And so does my game, Infernal Machine.

1012
00:49:30,875 --> 00:49:33,856
And these games always demand, and the stories,

1013
00:49:33,856 --> 00:49:37,218
always demand adventure and the supernatural.

1014
00:49:37,218 --> 00:49:39,578
Of course, the supernatural could be accomplished

1015
00:49:39,578 --> 00:49:43,160
with visual effects, but you can also do it with characters.

1016
00:49:43,160 --> 00:49:46,161
Here we are in Shambhala, in an abandoned monastery

1017
00:49:46,161 --> 00:49:47,861
inhabited by a lonely old woman.

1018
00:49:47,861 --> 00:49:50,062
If you run around and find a plant bulb,

1019
00:49:50,062 --> 00:49:53,944
nurse it into growth, and hand that thing to the old woman,

1020
00:49:53,944 --> 00:49:55,784
when it blooms, she's magically transformed

1021
00:49:55,784 --> 00:49:58,005
into a beautiful young princess.

1022
00:49:58,005 --> 00:50:00,366
Well, as beautiful as you can be with 100 polygons.

1023
00:50:01,655 --> 00:50:04,576
And anyway, she now requires the supernatural strength

1024
00:50:04,576 --> 00:50:08,577
to crack open a gate and send you on to even stranger things.

1025
00:50:08,577 --> 00:50:11,898
The adventure side, you need a pal and a guide.

1026
00:50:11,898 --> 00:50:14,798
We brought back Sophia Hapgood, this time

1027
00:50:14,798 --> 00:50:16,899
as an untrustworthy CIA agent.

1028
00:50:16,899 --> 00:50:19,059
But we didn't just want her to hang around.

1029
00:50:19,059 --> 00:50:21,020
So in the Palawan volcano level, she's

1030
00:50:21,020 --> 00:50:23,721
kidnapped by Russian Spetsnaz soldiers.

1031
00:50:23,721 --> 00:50:26,661
Meanwhile, Indy discovers a gate that blocks his path.

1032
00:50:27,146 --> 00:50:28,387
And there's a switch.

1033
00:50:28,387 --> 00:50:29,788
When pressed, the gate goes up.

1034
00:50:29,788 --> 00:50:31,790
When released, it comes right back down,

1035
00:50:31,790 --> 00:50:33,471
forcing him to rescue Sophia,

1036
00:50:33,471 --> 00:50:35,393
who then becomes his assistant.

1037
00:50:35,393 --> 00:50:36,934
She stands by the switch

1038
00:50:36,934 --> 00:50:38,995
as he readies himself to whip across a gap.

1039
00:50:38,995 --> 00:50:41,658
She presses the switch and holds it down long enough

1040
00:50:41,658 --> 00:50:43,099
for the gate to rise,

1041
00:50:43,099 --> 00:50:44,760
and Indy to whip his way across

1042
00:50:44,760 --> 00:50:46,161
and sneak inside just in time.

1043
00:50:46,161 --> 00:50:48,263
It's a co-op puzzle that anchors Sophia

1044
00:50:48,263 --> 00:50:50,525
into the gameplay, one of many.

1045
00:50:52,055 --> 00:50:56,997
The finale is a boss fight. We needed to pull the player through a long slog, and we needed

1046
00:50:56,997 --> 00:51:03,679
to give everything a supernatural twist. So the winged god Marduk, imagining that Sophia

1047
00:51:03,679 --> 00:51:08,681
might be a like-minded menace, captures her and melds with her. So when you fight and

1048
00:51:08,681 --> 00:51:13,183
win, you don't just earn a victory badge. You resolve a relationship and rescue a friend.

1049
00:51:13,183 --> 00:51:13,403
Now...

1050
00:51:16,314 --> 00:51:20,719
Here's a completely different kind of problem where you have a very mechanical game

1051
00:51:20,719 --> 00:51:23,122
and you need to introduce the NPCs and make them function.

1052
00:51:23,122 --> 00:51:28,649
So, not long ago I made a game involving Queen Titania and King Oberon

1053
00:51:28,649 --> 00:51:31,092
late of Shakespeare's Midsummer Night's Dream.

1054
00:51:32,302 --> 00:51:35,023
They're quarreling again and you need to reunite them.

1055
00:51:35,023 --> 00:51:35,824
It's an adventure RPG,

1056
00:51:35,824 --> 00:51:38,846
but it takes the form of slider puzzles.

1057
00:51:38,846 --> 00:51:41,868
The player maneuvers icons around the game board

1058
00:51:41,868 --> 00:51:45,630
in order to reveal and assemble the game elements.

1059
00:51:45,630 --> 00:51:47,531
Well, some of those icons turn into characters

1060
00:51:47,531 --> 00:51:50,713
and they speak, and that gives the game some human warmth.

1061
00:51:50,713 --> 00:51:53,195
And other characters need to be assembled

1062
00:51:53,195 --> 00:51:54,856
in order to be able to deal with them at all.

1063
00:51:54,856 --> 00:51:57,377
You even have to assemble the final boss

1064
00:51:57,377 --> 00:51:58,398
in order to do battle.

1065
00:51:59,622 --> 00:52:04,084
Well, if you think what I'm talking about is old-fashioned or adventurey and static,

1066
00:52:04,084 --> 00:52:10,988
antique, not so. Here's a perfectly modern game, The Last of Us. Joel, the hero, has

1067
00:52:10,988 --> 00:52:17,631
to deliver a serum across the country where it might become a cure for a fungus that's

1068
00:52:17,631 --> 00:52:18,632
destroyed civilization.

1069
00:52:19,621 --> 00:52:23,142
And that serum might have been liquid in a little glass vial in his pocket.

1070
00:52:23,142 --> 00:52:28,125
But if that were the case, the entire experience would be as dismal as this scene.

1071
00:52:28,125 --> 00:52:32,947
So instead, the serum resides in the immune system of a young woman, Ellie, his protege.

1072
00:52:32,947 --> 00:52:38,709
And the Naughty Dog designers didn't just want her to hang around either, so there are lots of co-op puzzles.

1073
00:52:39,044 --> 00:52:42,967
boosting her over walls, letting her crawl through tiny ducts to reach the far side of

1074
00:52:42,967 --> 00:52:47,030
a gate that Joel can't open from this side, and because she can't swim in at least three

1075
00:52:47,030 --> 00:52:52,593
instances, Joel has to find a raft to convey her across a body of water where she can do

1076
00:52:52,593 --> 00:52:53,954
her stuff.

1077
00:52:53,954 --> 00:52:56,056
She even has a level of her own.

1078
00:52:57,175 --> 00:52:59,998
Well, what's the takeaway from this sort of thing?

1079
00:52:59,998 --> 00:53:01,359
There are two.

1080
00:53:01,359 --> 00:53:03,020
One, humanize your design.

1081
00:53:03,020 --> 00:53:04,922
It's never a mistake to add characters,

1082
00:53:04,922 --> 00:53:09,446
especially if you can do so in unusual and functional ways.

1083
00:53:09,446 --> 00:53:12,928
But more generally, try to state the rules that do actually

1084
00:53:12,928 --> 00:53:16,071
guide you as explicitly as possible,

1085
00:53:16,071 --> 00:53:18,033
because that gives them power.

1086
00:53:18,033 --> 00:53:21,095
And try to run through them like a checklist,

1087
00:53:21,095 --> 00:53:22,656
deliberately, as you work.

1088
00:53:22,656 --> 00:53:23,437
You'll find that if you do.

1089
00:53:24,438 --> 00:53:27,559
your design vocabulary will be greatly enlarged.

1090
00:53:27,559 --> 00:53:31,480
This is my website, finitearts.com.

1091
00:53:31,480 --> 00:53:35,701
Here you can take a look at that rule collection,

1092
00:53:35,701 --> 00:53:38,522
see my old rule talks, play Thorne or play Yoda.

1093
00:53:38,522 --> 00:53:46,704
Thank you.

1094
00:53:46,704 --> 00:53:48,625
So weird that I just introduced Hal

1095
00:53:48,625 --> 00:53:50,445
after having seen him talk 15 years ago.

1096
00:53:51,297 --> 00:54:00,547
So, you know, the interesting thing about that rule set, I think, is, you know, his rule there is, you know, these are principles Hal's been using in games for ages.

1097
00:54:00,547 --> 00:54:03,650
Why can't everybody get on board with this at last?

1098
00:54:03,650 --> 00:54:09,437
Anyway, finally, we're coming up to Luke Muscat here, who...

1099
00:54:11,519 --> 00:54:16,281
You know, he's most known perhaps as the designer of games like Fruit Ninja, Jetpack Joyride.

1100
00:54:16,281 --> 00:54:23,824
He's now the creative director at Pretty Gate, where they worked on landsliders and other titles.

1101
00:54:23,824 --> 00:54:26,425
You know, and every year I do a talk like this, someone says,

1102
00:54:26,425 --> 00:54:29,566
yeah, really like a rule? Like, why are we doing rules?

1103
00:54:29,566 --> 00:54:31,207
And this year that person is Luke.

1104
00:54:31,207 --> 00:54:31,647
Here he is.

1105
00:54:49,327 --> 00:54:52,268
Okay, hi. Yeah, my name is Luke Muscat. I've made some stuff.

1106
00:54:52,268 --> 00:54:54,909
We're going a bit over time, so I'm gonna go a little bit faster.

1107
00:54:54,909 --> 00:54:59,171
So I'm basically here to say, forget your rules.

1108
00:54:59,171 --> 00:55:02,952
Make goals your king. It's all about just having strong goals.

1109
00:55:02,952 --> 00:55:07,394
Or, if you want the shorter, snappier, more twitterable

1110
00:55:07,394 --> 00:55:09,455
title for this talk, fuck rules.

1111
00:55:11,419 --> 00:55:16,541
Here's the problem I have with rules. Every time that I'm thinking about rules

1112
00:55:16,541 --> 00:55:18,182
or, you know, trying to kind of

1113
00:55:18,182 --> 00:55:22,384
process all of the knowledge and wisdom I've gotten from other designers and

1114
00:55:22,384 --> 00:55:23,124
through

1115
00:55:23,124 --> 00:55:25,285
making lots of games over the years,

1116
00:55:25,285 --> 00:55:28,906
it lets me take something, a feature that I'm making, and go from like

1117
00:55:29,287 --> 00:55:33,612
crap feature to something really good, and then all of a sudden I realize I've actually

1118
00:55:33,612 --> 00:55:35,334
been making the wrong thing all along.

1119
00:55:35,334 --> 00:55:38,198
So this is why I love goals.

1120
00:55:38,198 --> 00:55:41,763
It's always for me about keeping goals just to make sure I'm making the right thing.

1121
00:55:41,763 --> 00:55:43,044
And I'm going to give you an example.

1122
00:55:44,255 --> 00:55:47,138
So let's say this could be like a design document or

1123
00:55:47,138 --> 00:55:50,281
whatever, for this will be like a user story and a

1124
00:55:50,281 --> 00:55:52,143
sprint backlog.

1125
00:55:52,143 --> 00:55:54,185
We're going to make a health bar.

1126
00:55:54,185 --> 00:55:57,409
And we have a list of tasks there to make that health bar,

1127
00:55:57,409 --> 00:56:00,272
and then a kind of estimate of how long we think it might

1128
00:56:00,272 --> 00:56:01,533
take to make it.

1129
00:56:01,533 --> 00:56:02,674
So here we go.

1130
00:56:02,674 --> 00:56:03,535
Here's our health bar.

1131
00:56:03,535 --> 00:56:03,776
And.

1132
00:56:05,898 --> 00:56:07,819
Like that health bar sucks, right?

1133
00:56:07,819 --> 00:56:09,520
That's one shitty health bar.

1134
00:56:09,520 --> 00:56:10,480
So what do I do?

1135
00:56:10,480 --> 00:56:12,561
Well, I think about the first thing

1136
00:56:12,561 --> 00:56:14,703
that I learned as a designer, which is it's

1137
00:56:14,703 --> 00:56:16,383
all about player feedback.

1138
00:56:16,383 --> 00:56:18,344
You've got to make it juicy and exciting,

1139
00:56:18,344 --> 00:56:21,146
and then that's going to make this health bar really good.

1140
00:56:21,146 --> 00:56:23,407
So let's iterate this health bar real quick.

1141
00:56:23,407 --> 00:56:26,409
We can add a little bit of art, so at least it

1142
00:56:26,409 --> 00:56:27,109
doesn't look so placeholder.

1143
00:56:27,109 --> 00:56:27,649
And then, whoops.

1144
00:56:31,505 --> 00:56:34,326
we can add a bit of animation there as well.

1145
00:56:34,326 --> 00:56:37,707
So now you can see really clearly exactly how much health

1146
00:56:37,707 --> 00:56:38,767
you've lost.

1147
00:56:38,767 --> 00:56:40,188
And then we add particles.

1148
00:56:40,188 --> 00:56:41,348
Yeah, particles.

1149
00:56:41,348 --> 00:56:43,189
Everyone loves particles, right?

1150
00:56:43,189 --> 00:56:46,750
And then we can step it up and add some screen shake as well.

1151
00:56:46,750 --> 00:56:48,871
And now we have a health bar that's kind of cool.

1152
00:56:48,871 --> 00:56:51,212
And of course, we can just keep on going and going and going

1153
00:56:51,212 --> 00:56:52,373
and make this better and better.

1154
00:56:53,033 --> 00:56:55,236
And what we've done is we've taken an idea

1155
00:56:55,236 --> 00:56:57,539
and then we've implemented it and then we've iterated

1156
00:56:57,539 --> 00:57:00,022
on that implementation to make it as good as possible

1157
00:57:00,022 --> 00:57:01,764
and then we're done.

1158
00:57:01,764 --> 00:57:05,149
And even kind of like the dangerous part of this

1159
00:57:05,149 --> 00:57:06,771
is I love that health bar, right?

1160
00:57:06,771 --> 00:57:08,994
Like I just sunk a whole bunch of time into that health bar.

1161
00:57:10,122 --> 00:57:12,924
But, I mean, why was I making a health bar again?

1162
00:57:12,924 --> 00:57:15,786
Like, clearly I thought it was a good idea at some point,

1163
00:57:15,786 --> 00:57:17,447
but at this point I've completely forgotten

1164
00:57:17,447 --> 00:57:18,988
what the purpose of this health bar was.

1165
00:57:18,988 --> 00:57:21,329
And even if I remember why it's on there,

1166
00:57:21,329 --> 00:57:23,251
in the design document or whatever,

1167
00:57:23,251 --> 00:57:25,372
you can bet my programmers and artists don't know.

1168
00:57:26,993 --> 00:57:30,657
So this is the thing, this is, you know, we always have like, you know, the vision, which

1169
00:57:30,657 --> 00:57:33,800
is like our really big goal for the game, and then we have the design pillars, which

1170
00:57:33,800 --> 00:57:36,863
are like the ones in the middle, and then like the user stories, or like, you know,

1171
00:57:36,863 --> 00:57:40,426
the feature kind of goals, and then all of a sudden we're implementing it, and for me,

1172
00:57:40,426 --> 00:57:43,269
like, I just completely forget all that other stuff.

1173
00:57:43,269 --> 00:57:45,251
And you know, implementation is hard.

1174
00:57:45,772 --> 00:57:48,555
And I think that's why it kind of goes over the top of all of that.

1175
00:57:48,555 --> 00:57:52,961
I mean, a lot of the talks at GDC are about the best way to implement something.

1176
00:57:52,961 --> 00:57:54,302
How do you make something more efficient?

1177
00:57:54,302 --> 00:57:57,867
How do you make it even better, have a better emotional response?

1178
00:57:59,221 --> 00:58:03,502
And so what I try and do is actually make it really explicit

1179
00:58:03,502 --> 00:58:07,503
that I need to hit my goals. And you can do that with a few really simple little

1180
00:58:07,503 --> 00:58:11,484
tweaks. So instead of a user story, I can set a goal here and go, okay, the player can

1181
00:58:11,484 --> 00:58:14,924
take multiple hits and knows when they will die. I mean, that's basically like

1182
00:58:14,924 --> 00:58:17,005
the goal of a health bar, right?

1183
00:58:17,005 --> 00:58:21,826
And now, instead of having a list of tasks, we have a list of possible solutions.

1184
00:58:21,826 --> 00:58:24,426
There is definitely more than one way to skin this cat.

1185
00:58:25,667 --> 00:58:27,249
Tricky part is, is now effort.

1186
00:58:27,249 --> 00:58:29,572
We don't know exactly what we're making, right?

1187
00:58:29,572 --> 00:58:31,374
So how do we calculate the effort?

1188
00:58:31,374 --> 00:58:32,776
Well, I think that's fine.

1189
00:58:32,776 --> 00:58:34,018
We could do even better.

1190
00:58:34,018 --> 00:58:35,720
Let's set a budget instead.

1191
00:58:35,720 --> 00:58:38,323
How important is it that we hit this goal

1192
00:58:38,323 --> 00:58:39,605
and really nail it?

1193
00:58:39,605 --> 00:58:41,307
And let's scale the amount of work

1194
00:58:41,307 --> 00:58:43,229
based on not how much there is to do,

1195
00:58:43,229 --> 00:58:44,310
but how important it is.

1196
00:58:45,577 --> 00:58:49,020
And this way it really explicitly allows us to iterate on an idea first

1197
00:58:49,020 --> 00:58:52,624
before we iterate on the implementation.

1198
00:58:52,624 --> 00:58:55,027
And really, I put this goal everywhere

1199
00:58:55,027 --> 00:58:57,830
just so that I invoke my inner three-year-old,

1200
00:58:57,830 --> 00:59:00,073
which is just to keep asking why.

1201
00:59:00,073 --> 00:59:02,435
Why? Why are we doing this? To make it more fun.

1202
00:59:02,435 --> 00:59:04,277
Yeah, but like, why? Does it need to be fun?

1203
00:59:04,277 --> 00:59:07,200
And just keep on drilling back further and further.

1204
00:59:07,881 --> 00:59:10,322
And you know, we can make this goal way better as well.

1205
00:59:10,322 --> 00:59:12,263
We can iterate on the goal and go,

1206
00:59:12,263 --> 00:59:14,885
okay, let's try and create exciting moments

1207
00:59:14,885 --> 00:59:16,986
where the player barely scrapes through an area.

1208
00:59:16,986 --> 00:59:19,167
That's really what this health bar was about

1209
00:59:19,167 --> 00:59:20,047
in the first place, right?

1210
00:59:20,047 --> 00:59:22,588
And there's so many ways we could do that.

1211
00:59:22,588 --> 00:59:24,249
Health bar is totally one of those ways.

1212
00:59:24,249 --> 00:59:26,130
This isn't saying like, don't do health bars.

1213
00:59:26,130 --> 00:59:27,251
Maybe that is the best way,

1214
00:59:27,251 --> 00:59:29,852
and maybe for, you know, the amount of budget we have,

1215
00:59:29,852 --> 00:59:30,773
maybe that's what works.

1216
00:59:32,802 --> 00:59:36,485
So, when I was doing Jetpack Joyride, we had this exact problem, right?

1217
00:59:36,485 --> 00:59:39,407
This is basically what it looked like at one point. It's a cave flyer.

1218
00:59:39,407 --> 00:59:42,469
One touch, dodge stuff, if something hits you, you die.

1219
00:59:42,469 --> 00:59:43,510
And that's it.

1220
00:59:43,510 --> 00:59:47,813
And you know, it was already looking like this. It was quite polished and pretty fun, but we just...

1221
00:59:47,813 --> 00:59:49,954
I mean, I wasn't quite feeling it.

1222
00:59:49,954 --> 00:59:52,636
It just wasn't quite there yet, I didn't think.

1223
00:59:52,636 --> 00:59:55,078
It felt a little one-note and a little repetitive.

1224
00:59:55,078 --> 00:59:58,921
So I go, okay, my goal is obviously to add some variety.

1225
00:59:58,921 --> 00:59:59,881
How am I gonna add variety?

1226
01:00:01,018 --> 01:00:06,662
power-ups. Duh. Like that's obviously the way that I'll do it. And we spent ages

1227
01:00:06,662 --> 01:00:10,365
working on power-ups and it just, I mean, it helped. There was more variety, there

1228
01:00:10,365 --> 01:00:16,150
was more things to do, but it just wasn't quite there. And really the reason is, is

1229
01:00:16,150 --> 01:00:20,954
this goal sucks. Make the game more interesting? Like what does that even

1230
01:00:20,954 --> 01:00:24,496
mean? My possible solutions are power-ups and maybe something else.

1231
01:00:25,358 --> 01:00:30,142
We really gotta give that goal a bit of love and make that a better goal.

1232
01:00:30,142 --> 01:00:35,146
And so we realized after a while playing around with it, it wasn't just that it needed more

1233
01:00:35,146 --> 01:00:40,290
variety, like the intensity really specifically needed more variety.

1234
01:00:40,290 --> 01:00:45,113
Because the game starts slow and then speeds up and you're always one hit away from death.

1235
01:00:45,113 --> 01:00:49,536
And so your intensity just starts low, ramps up and then you're just like maxed out the

1236
01:00:49,536 --> 01:00:50,217
whole time.

1237
01:00:50,217 --> 01:00:52,499
And then that makes it feel really one note.

1238
01:00:53,279 --> 01:00:57,040
And I realize, like, you know, the variety problem isn't necessarily about power-ups

1239
01:00:57,040 --> 01:00:59,060
or having different things to do.

1240
01:00:59,060 --> 01:01:01,261
It's actually a health problem, right?

1241
01:01:01,261 --> 01:01:05,422
If I add three hearts, for example, all of a sudden we get a dramatically different intensity

1242
01:01:05,422 --> 01:01:05,822
curve.

1243
01:01:05,822 --> 01:01:10,103
You start off really low, you hit something, and all of a sudden you're like, ooh, okay,

1244
01:01:10,103 --> 01:01:13,024
I've only got one more hit left and then I'm on my last hit.

1245
01:01:13,024 --> 01:01:16,284
Or we could do, like, a regenerating health thing, like in a Call of Duty or whatever.

1246
01:01:16,284 --> 01:01:19,905
And they all give really different intensities and feeling to the game.

1247
01:01:19,905 --> 01:01:22,706
It's really about health, not about adding power-ups.

1248
01:01:23,806 --> 01:01:27,568
And we kind of ended up with this system, which is the vehicle system, where every now

1249
01:01:27,568 --> 01:01:32,529
and then you'll find a vehicle and it'll actually change the controls and everything.

1250
01:01:32,529 --> 01:01:38,332
And you know, it stops and slows down the whole game and it kind of starts you off again.

1251
01:01:38,332 --> 01:01:42,633
Really the vehicle is just the most elaborate health pack pickup you've ever seen.

1252
01:01:42,633 --> 01:01:47,375
Eventually I'll hit something and blow up and now you're back into the same cadence

1253
01:01:47,375 --> 01:01:47,875
as before.

1254
01:01:48,655 --> 01:01:52,179
And this gives us this really interesting intensity curve.

1255
01:01:52,179 --> 01:01:55,181
It's just this kind of weird love child of a health system

1256
01:01:55,181 --> 01:01:56,363
and a power-up system.

1257
01:01:56,363 --> 01:01:58,585
And it became a really iconic part of the game

1258
01:01:58,585 --> 01:02:00,246
and a big factor of its success.

1259
01:02:02,376 --> 01:02:05,978
So some pros to kind of working this way, I mean, other than the ones I've kind of

1260
01:02:05,978 --> 01:02:07,599
obviously already laid out,

1261
01:02:07,599 --> 01:02:11,442
my favorite thing is that it really helps the team all pull in the same

1262
01:02:11,442 --> 01:02:12,342
direction.

1263
01:02:12,342 --> 01:02:13,883
You know, like when a programmer

1264
01:02:13,883 --> 01:02:17,125
comes to you and has some crazy feature that they just worked on on the side,

1265
01:02:17,125 --> 01:02:20,887
they come up with some, you know, batshit crazy thing that they

1266
01:02:20,887 --> 01:02:24,610
really like and sometimes, like fifty percent of the time it's super cool and ends up in

1267
01:02:24,610 --> 01:02:28,212
the game and fifty percent of the time you're like, well that's cool but like,

1268
01:02:28,212 --> 01:02:28,952
why did you do that?

1269
01:02:30,013 --> 01:02:35,816
If your goals are always really explicitly stated everywhere, it means there's a really good chance

1270
01:02:35,816 --> 01:02:38,997
that they'll be pulling in the right direction and come up with something cool that you didn't

1271
01:02:38,997 --> 01:02:44,680
even think of that helps you achieve that goal. Even better, it helps them kind of check me to

1272
01:02:44,680 --> 01:02:48,923
make sure I'm trying to hit those goals because I might start implementing something and they're

1273
01:02:48,923 --> 01:02:51,564
like, what are you sure that actually achieves what you were trying to do?

1274
01:02:53,001 --> 01:02:57,462
